\begin_layout Section
Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DNA-protein interactions are shown by using chromatin immunoprecipitation.
 Chromatin immunoprecipitation uses a specific antibody to target a protein
 of interest, in our case a transcription factor, and then it targets that
 protein and links it with fragments of DNA from a cell lysate.
 The DNA-protein complex is precipitated from the mixture and the proteins
 are unlinked from the DNA fragments which results in a library of DNA fragments
 that are enriched for the binding sites we are interested in.
 The short reads are typically 20-25 base pairs (bp) and they are aligned
 to a reference genome using fast alignment algorithms.
 Overall, the ChIP-seq approach provides a whole-genome view of the transcriptio
n factors activity.
 
\end_layout

